<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-952-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 952 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  Dec 11 1989 v139 pC1(N) pD1(L) 24 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Phone-call thieves hitting corporations' switchboards. (computerhackers costing companies millions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sims, Calvin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer hackers are increasingly using long distance access codesstolen from corporations to make free phone calls, costingcorporation hundreds of millions of dollars a year.andP;  The codes areobtained using software on a home computer.andP;  The software triesvarious combinations of four digits, repeatedly calling acorporation's switchboard until an access code works.andP;  The codesare then posted on hackers' electronic bulletin boards.andP;  Longdistance carriers suggest several steps to preventing this form ofcomputer crime.andP;  Companies should make access codes longer, cancelaccess codes of former employees immediately, alert switchboardoperators to the various schemes, block international calls exceptto countries where legitimate business is conducted and monitordaily phone records closely.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FraudTelephone SystemsAccess MethodsComputer Crimes.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>